post_cb({"18880626": {"Id": "18880626", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>I would call it a scope. I think that's what others call it too.</p>\n", "OwnerDisplayName": "user1356386", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-18T19:25:29.070", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-09-18T19:25:29.070", "ParentId": "18880611", "CommentCount": "0"}, "18880658": {"Id": "18880658", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>You are <em>shadowing</em> an existing variable. This is not good programming practice.</p>\n<p>Out of interest, Java forbids it.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-18T19:27:39.023", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-09-18T19:27:39.023", "ParentId": "18880611", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "2380830"}, "18880865": {"Id": "18880865", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>it is simply called scope of a variable.c permits us to define samevariable name variables .</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-18T19:38:28.437", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-09-18T19:38:28.437", "ParentId": "18880611", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "2694273"}, "18880643": {"Id": "18880643", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The <code>{ ... }</code> is a <em>block</em> or <em>compound statement</em>, which creates a nested <em>scope</em>. (It's not a <code>namespace</code>.)</p>\n<p>This particular case, of a declaration in an inner scope having the same name as (and therefore hiding) a declaration in an outer scope is sometimes called <em>shadowing</em>.</p>\n<p>g++ can warn about this. Quoting <a href=\"http://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc-4.8.1/gcc/Warning-Options.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">the manual</a>:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-none prettyprint-override\"><code>`-Wshadow'\n     Warn whenever a local variable or type declaration shadows another\n     variable, parameter, type, or class member (in C++), or whenever a\n     built-in function is shadowed. Note that in C++, the compiler will\n     not warn if a local variable shadows a struct/class/enum, but will\n     warn if it shadows an explicit typedef.\n</code></pre>\n<p>(As Adam Rosenfield points out in a comment, <code>-Wshadow</code> is not enabled by <code>-Wall</code>, <code>-Wextra</code>, or <code>-pedantic</code>; you have to enable it explicitly.)</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "827263", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-18T19:46:49.000", "Score": "8", "CreationDate": "2013-09-18T19:26:23.733", "ParentId": "18880611", "CommentCount": "1", "OwnerUserId": "827263", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-18T19:46:49.000"}, "18880678": {"Id": "18880678", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>I think what you're referring to is variable hiding, or variable shadowing. By declaring a variable in the inner scope with the same name as the outer scope, you are hiding the outer variable from the inner scope. Obviously in more complicated code this could be confusing. </p>\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_shadowing\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_shadowing</a></p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-18T19:28:31.273", "CommentCount": "4", "CreationDate": "2013-09-18T19:28:31.273", "ParentId": "18880611", "Score": "3", "OwnerUserId": "2705103"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_18880611_18880713_1": {"length": 22, "quality": 0.88, "section_id": 7061}, "so_18880611_18880713_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3881}}, "n3337": {"so_18880611_18880713_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3741}, "so_18880611_18880713_1": {"length": 22, "quality": 0.88, "section_id": 6805}}, "n4659": {"so_18880611_18880713_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 4770}, "so_18880611_18880713_1": {"length": 22, "quality": 0.88, "section_id": 8558}}}, "18880713": {"Id": "18880713", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>There is two concepts going on here, one you are creating a <code>block scope</code> within the <code>{ ... }</code> and you are hiding the outer instance of <code>variable</code> within this block scope. A block scope is being created by a compound statement(<em>or block</em>), if we look at the C++ draft standard section <code>6.3</code> <em>Compound statement or block</em> paragraph <em>1</em> has the following grammar:</p>\n<pre><code>compound-statement:\n  { statement-seqopt}\n</code></pre>\n<p>it also says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_18880611_18880713_0\">A compound statement defines a block scope (3.3).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>and if we look at section <code>3.3.3</code> <em>3.3.3 Block scope</em> paragraph <em>1</em> says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_18880611_18880713_1\">A name declared in a block (6.3) is local to that block; it has block scope. Its potential scope begins at its point of declaration (3.3.2) and ends at the end of its block. A variable declared at block scope is a local variable.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So what is happening with <code>variable</code> is that the local copy in the inner block is <code>hiding</code> the instance of <code>variable</code> in the outer block since it has the same name.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "1708801", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-18T20:00:28.150", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-09-18T19:30:19.953", "ParentId": "18880611", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "1708801", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-18T20:00:28.150"}, "18880611": {"ViewCount": "150", "Body": "<p>Ok so I have this code and I KNOW it's not good programming practice. I just forgot what it's called. </p>\n<pre><code>int main()\n{\n    int variable; \n    {\n        int variable;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Is that a local namespace or something? I just can't remember the correct term for doing something such as that.</p>\n", "Title": "I forgot what this is called?", "CreationDate": "2013-09-18T19:23:46.410", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-18T20:00:28.150", "CommentCount": "3", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "18880611", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "1772419", "Tags": "<c++><namespaces><scope>", "AnswerCount": "6"}});